problem link https://leetcode.com/problems/search-a-2d-matrix/description/
Intuition
Since the first element of every row is greater than the last element of the previous row, the matrix can be viewed as a collection of sorted ranges.

Instead of searching the entire matrix directly, I first determine which row could possibly contain the target. The correct row is the last row whose first element is less than or equal to the target.

Once that row is identified, I perform a standard binary search within that row.

Approach
Perform a binary search on the rows using the first element of each row.
If matrix[mid][0] <= target, this row is a possible candidate, but a later row may also satisfy the condition, so store the row index and continue searching to the right.
Otherwise, search the left half.
If no valid row is found, return False.
Perform a standard binary search on the identified row.
Return True if the target is found.
Otherwise, return False.

This approach efficiently narrows the search space using two binary searches.

Algorithm
Initialize low = 0 and high = number of rows - 1.
Binary search to find the last row whose first element is less than or equal to the target.
If no such row exists, return False.
Binary search within the selected row.
Return True if the target is found; otherwise return False.
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity: O(log m + log n)
O(log m) to identify the candidate row.
O(log n) to search within that row.
Space Complexity: O(1)
Key Observation

The important observation is that every row represents a sorted interval, and these intervals do not overlap because

the rows are individually sorted, and
the first element of each row is greater than the last element of the previous row.

Therefore, the target can belong to at most one row, allowing us to first locate the correct row and then perform a binary search within it.

Code
class Solution:
    def searchMatrix(self, matrix: List[List[int]], target: int) -> bool:
        low = 0
        high = len(matrix) - 1
        resultant_row = None
        while low <= high:
            mid = (low+high)//2
            if matrix[mid][0] <= target:
                resultant_row = mid
                low = mid + 1
            else:
                high = mid - 1
        if resultant_row == None:
            return False
        low = 0
        high = len(matrix[resultant_row]) - 1
        while low <= high:
            mid = (low+high)//2
            if matrix[resultant_row][mid] == target:
                return True
            elif matrix[resultant_row][mid] < target:
                low = mid + 1
            else:
                high = mid - 1
        return False
